Program Intention :
===============================================================================================
system call munmap( ) destroys a memory mapping
Creating an anonymous memory mapping is actually easier than creating a file backed mapping, as
there is no file to open and manage.

===============================================================================================
COMPILE :

  all done with 'p', so give back the 512 KB mapping
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg278_munmap$ make
gcc -Wall -g -o pg278_munmap pg278_munmap.c;

===============================================================================================
Execution:

linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg278_munmap$ ./pg278_munmap

  all done with 'p', so give back the 512 KB mapping
linux@linux:~/Linux_programming/Chapter7_Memory_Management/pg278_munmap$ 

===============================================================================================
Program Flow
===============================================================================================
    The system call munmap( ) frees an anonymous mapping, returning the allocated memory to 
    the kernel.





